An alternative release scenario for SPP is that aqueous ammonia is spilled while the tanks are being filled.  In this scenario, it's assumed that enough gallons of aqueous ammonia spill into the containment dike to cover the full area of the containment dike. Under the EPA's RMP Guidance for Offsite Consequence Analysis, the alternate release scenario meteorological conditions are 3.0 meters per second wind speed and an atmospheric stability class of D stability for urban releases.  In the alternate release scenario the ammonia cloud could travel 0.1 miles (528feet) before dispersing sufficiently to no longer pose a health hazard to the public.  The impact distance from an alternate release scenario also extends beyond the facility property.

To prevent future potential ammonia accidents with offsite impacts, Chugach has established the following practices:

?    The facility utilizes an extensive, interconnected alarm system to monitor the tanks;

?    Access to the site is restricted via guard gates to authorized personnel;

?    All facility personnel are trained on safe work practices and the proper procedures to be followed should a leak or spill occur;

?    Spills are contained in the dike, minimizing the impact distance;

?    The tanks and unloading areas are situated away from the main process area, such that if an accident were to occur, the area of highest impact would generally be away from employees; and

?    Tanks are inspected to ensure their integrity.

There have been no accidental releases from the aqueous ammonia storage and handling system at the facility in the past five years.  Aqueous ammonia use will only begin in the second half of 2012 at SPP.

